Inner Class in Java

An inner class is a non-static class defined inside another class.

👉 It is tightly connected to an instance of the outer class.

Basic Example
class Outer {
    class Inner {
        void print() {
            System.out.println("Hello from inner class");
        }
    }
}
Creating an Object
Outer outer = new Outer();
Outer.Inner inner = outer.new Inner();

inner.print();

👉 Inner class requires an outer class object

Key Features
does NOT use static
depends on outer class instance
can access all members of outer class (even private)
used for strong logical connection
Accessing Outer Class Members
class Outer {
    private int x = 10;

    class Inner {
        void print() {
            System.out.println(x); // ✅ can access private field
        }
    }
}
Why use Inner Class?

Use it when:

one class is strongly related to another
you need access to outer class data
want better encapsulation
Real-Life Idea

👉 Inner class = “helper” that belongs to a specific object

Example:

Car → inner class Engine
User → inner class Address
Inner Class vs Static Nested Class
Feature	Inner Class	Static Nested Class
Needs outer object	✅	❌
Access instance fields	✅	❌
Access static fields	✅	✅
Important Notes
cannot exist without outer object
often used for cleaner design
can make code more readable when used correctly
Summary
inner class = class inside another class (non-static)
tied to outer class instance
can access all outer class members
useful for encapsulation and structure
